  "Idea": "We propose Emotion-Aware Dynamic Graph Networks (EADGN), a novel framework for multi-party dialogue emotion recognition that introduces a joint, bidirectional update mechanism for both the relational graph structure and the temporal evolution of emotional states. Unlike existing GNN-based approaches that assume a static or pre-defined conversation graph, EADGN treats the interaction topology as a latent, dynamically evolving entity that adapts based on utterance content, speaker roles, and observed emotional shifts. At its core, EADGN employs two co-adaptive components: (1) a Temporal Emotion State Propagator (TESP), which models each participant’s emotional trajectory using a gated recurrent unit enhanced with self-attention over multimodal inputs (text, audio, visual), and (2) a Graph Topology Learner (GTL), which generates time-varying edge weights by evaluating emotional influence potential between speakers using a differentiable, attention-based influence function. Crucially, these components interact iteratively: emotional state changes in TESP trigger structural updates in GTL (e.g., increasing connection strength between empathetic speakers), while new graph configurations modulate future message passing in TESP. To capture delayed emotional reactions and memory effects, we introduce a spike-inspired decay mechanism in node states, mimicking how humans retain and gradually forget emotional stimuli. The full model is trained end-to-end using a hybrid loss combining emotion classification accuracy and graph coherence regularization (to prevent overfitting to transient noise). By explicitly modeling the feedback loop between affective dynamics and relational restructuring, EADGN enables more accurate and interpretable emotion prediction in complex dialogues involving interruptions, group consensus, and emotional cascades. This framework addresses key limitations in current methods—such as rigid graph assumptions and poor handling of non-local depende